Wings?

18
00:04:05,549 --> 00:04:06,445
Wings.

19
00:04:06,723 --> 00:04:12,187
God forbid! This is a publishing house,
not a birdhouse!

20
00:04:12,603 --> 00:04:17,985
Things. Have you read the poems I left?

21
00:04:18,161 --> 00:04:19,217
I have.

22
00:04:19,692 --> 00:04:22,800
Did you like them? You'll publish them?

23
00:04:23,069 --> 00:04:25,731
Why? Am I crazy?

24
00:04:26,070 --> 00:04:30,101
Call that poetry? It's a crusade
against hunger and unemployment.

25
00:04:31,416 --> 00:04:35,283
Sir, poetry deals with delicacies.

26
00:04:35,992 --> 00:04:38,076
Write poems about flowers and songbirds.

27
00:04:38,534 --> 00:04:40,286
You're incomparable, sir!

28
00:04:41,163 --> 00:04:43,708
Write about wine and the carafe...

29
00:04:43,862 --> 00:04:49,713
the delicate neck of the carafe,
the curve of a woman's eyebrow.

30
00:04:49,792 --> 00:04:53,256
Be quiet! Are you a poet or a barber?

31
00:04:53,337 --> 00:04:55,169
Have you studied poets like Mir and Momin?

32
00:04:55,493 --> 00:04:56,857
Have you?

33
00:04:57,296 --> 00:05:02,841
Josh and Faiz, too. Beyond your
comprehension. Return my poems.

34
00:05:03,175 --> 00:05:05,404
They must be somewhere. We'll find them later.

35
00:05:10,263 --> 00:05:17,310
You're making a mess of my papers.
Are you mad?

36
00:05:18,067 --> 00:05:20,133
What is this? Oh no.

37
00:05:20,913 --> 00:05:21,841
...

38
00:05:23,980 --> 00:05:28,605
So that's where my poems were.
Who are you to throw them away?

39
00:05:28,983 --> 00:05:31,900
Should I make a paper hat of them?

40
00:05:32,235 --> 00:05:35,861
Don't insult them by wearing them
on a hollow head.

41
00:05:37,113 --> 00:05:38,660
- So my head is hollow? - Yes.

42
00:05:39,449 --> 00:05:43,984
How about yours?
If you're a poet, I'm a donkey!

43
00:05:45,297 --> 00:05:48,638
Obviously, but it's nice to hear you admit it.

44
00:06:02,336 --> 00:06:05,712
Are you weighing vegetables or gold?
Add another eggplant.

45
00:06:07,220 --> 00:06:08,079
Come on.

46
00:06:09,760 --> 00:06:11,174
Grandma, there's Uncle Vijay

47
00:06:13,135 --> 00:06:14,923
Vijay. Here's you money.

48
00:06:16,967 --> 00:06:19,402
- Uncle. - Vijay.

49
00:06:20,516 --> 00:06:23,913
- Uncle. - Vijay.

50
00:06:30,943 --> 00:06:32,510
Vijay.

51
00:06:33,485 --> 00:06:34,729
Grandma, hurry up.

52
00:06:37,196 --> 00:06:38,732
I've caught Uncle.

53
00:06:49,225 --> 00:06:54,457
I'm not your enemy. Why run from your mother?

54
00:06:54,763 --> 00:06:56,647
- Mom I...
- Son, where have you been all these days?

55
00:06:57,828 --> 00:07:02,073
You lost your father.
I can't bear to see you suffer.

56
00:07:02,872 --> 00:07:04,068
I'm well, mother.

57
00:07:04,415 --> 00:07:09,209
Of course! Just look at the state you're in.

58
00:07:10,419 --> 00:07:16,768
Come home. I've hidden away
some special food for you.

59
00:07:16,848 --> 00:07:18,552
Come my son.

60
00:07:18,632 --> 00:07:20,792
You've found him?

61
00:07:21,062 --> 00:07:22,879
Yes.

62
00:07:22,959 --> 00:07:24,265
Come my son.

63
00:07:28,850 --> 00:07:33,382
Vijay had such a promising future.
Look at him now.

64
00:07:34,390 --> 00:07:36,865
I hear poetry has obsessed him.

65
00:07:44,881 --> 00:07:47,140
Take no notice of them. Eat.

66
00:07:51,569 --> 00:07:54,443
So your poet is back?

67
00:07:57,072 --> 00:08:00,079
Every literate donkey thinks he's a poet.

68
00:08:00,737 --> 00:08:02,058
Brother.

69
00:08:02,349 --> 00:08:05,909
Where else can he go? Who will feed him?

70
00:08:06,077 --> 00:08:08,661
Don't listen to him. Eat.

71
00:08:14,022 --> 00:08:20,336
See, brother? We earn and mother
feeds delicacies to her darling son.

72
00:08:20,782 --> 00:08:23,337
His lack of shame amazes me.

73
00:08:23,754 --> 00:08:29,425
If he had any self-respect,
he'd starve rather than eat here.

74
00:08:33,469 --> 00:08:39,216
Shut up, you two!
I won't hear a word said against him.

75
00:08:39,679 --> 00:08:45,017
He's back after so long, thirsty
and hungry, and you begrudge him.

76
00:08:45,225 --> 00:08:50,088
He's hale and hearty. Why doesn't
he earn his keep? Depending on us.

77
00:08:50,552 --> 00:08:55,221
He's your brother. After father
died you should look after him.

78
00:08:55,838 --> 00:08:58,930
Father has gone and with him his duty.

79
00:08:59,136 --> 00:09:02,392
It wasn't our wish that our parents
produced such a good-for-nothing.

80
00:09:02,657 --> 00:09:03,738
...

81
00:09:04,394 --> 00:09:05,400
What?

82
00:09:07,312 --> 00:09:09,178
That I should have to hear this.

83
00:09:10,821 --> 00:09:14,055
It was my misfortune to give birth to you two.

84
00:09:14,596 --> 00:09:18,004
You won't let me work as a maid
because of your "prestige."

85
00:09:20,809 --> 00:09:24,270
I would do that to feed my son.

86
00:09:26,426 --> 00:09:27,862
...

87
00:09:28,606 --> 00:09:30,986
Sister-in-law, where are my poems?

88
00:09:31,288 --> 00:09:34,500
Address me, not the women.

89
00:09:34,693 --> 00:09:37,204
I sold them as waste paper for ten annas.

90
00:09:45,253 --> 00:09:52,204
Ten annas? You sold my poems as waste paper?

91
00:09:55,331 --> 00:09:57,422
Uncouth fools like you know no better.

92
00:09:57,747 --> 00:10:03,252
You call me uncouth?
Did you hear that, brother?

93
00:10:03,665 --> 00:10:10,447
How dare you? I got rid of your papers,
now I'll get rid of you!

94
00:10:10,528 --> 00:10:13,692
Out! Useless!

95
00:10:18,678 --> 00:10:26,641
Where will you go on an empty stomach?
Who will look after you?

96
00:10:27,895 --> 00:10:33,645
Take me with you. I don't want to
stay in this house another minute

97
00:10:34,937 --> 00:10:38,856
Don't worry, mother. I'll do my best.

98
00:10:40,315 --> 00:10:45,401
I'll take you away from here as soon as I can.

99
00:10:54,464 --> 00:10:59,369
Vijay, let me get on with my work
instead of searching waste paper.

100
